Here is someone repairing my kitchen floor just now. And I'm pretending I still have a job and am working from home while I'm actually writing for Too Hot to Handle.
If I fucking managed to open the file. (Fucking OneDrive.)
The translation of the sentence "*Stimme eines Hackers* Ich bin drin." from German to English is:  *Hacker's Voice* I'm in.
And that's when he starts drilling super loud. Hurrah.
It feels uncomfortably passive-aggressive to turn up my air purifier all the way, but I can smell the wood dust, so it would even be completely okay if he weren't against wearing a mask. Do I really need to protect myself?
I would really like to go back to bed, but I can't do that before he leaves.
At least I finally finished revising Chapter 4!
Chapter five is long, but so damn terrifying. Oh yeah, that's the good stuff!
I am doing a search and replace for ... ➡️ Ellipsis symbol, and there are 54 of them in this chapter 😅
But no, I stick to my point. Natural language is usually fragmented, especially when one becomes emotional.
The craftsman is now using the vacuum cleaner. Hopefully, that means he will be finished soon.
He went out to cut something (that's how it sounds anyway). I secretly checked how far he had gone. There's still a lot to do :(.
There are still 7 pages left in Chapter 5. It's still my favorite chapter, and it's quite tidy – mainly changes in the writing and very small corrections in direct speech, and I need to formulate everything a bit more compactly. But I really could use a break and a cup of tea, but that guy is still in my kitchen.
He has just started vacuuming again. Hopefully, that's a good sign.
The kitchen type is gone!
He told me that he had made a cost estimate for the entire floor, but the landlords were too tight-fisted and only paid for the part next to the door, which is no longer in good condition. It feels much better this way.
The house is well-ventilated and my air purifier is running in the kitchen, while I am drinking tea in the garden!
